NEW YORK, Oct. 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S.-listed Chinese companies traded mostly higher on Thursday with six of the top 10 stocks by weight in the S&P U.S. Listed China 50 index ending the day on an upbeat note. Shares of NIO and Baidu rose 3.76 percent and 0.57 percent, respectively, leading the gainers in the top 10 stocks in the index. Shares of Yum China Holdings and NetEase dipped 1.28 percent and 0.37 percent, respectively, leading the laggards in the top 10 stocks. U.S. stocks advanced on Thursday as investors parsed a slew of earnings reports and economic data. The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 239.79 points, or 0.68 percent, to 35,730.48. The S&P 500 was up 44.74 points, or 0.98 percent, to 4,596.42. The Nasdaq Composite Index increased 212.28 points, or 1.39 percent, to 15,448.12. The Cboe Volatility Index, widely considered as the best fear gauge in the stock market, dropped 2.65 percent to 16.53. As of Wednesday, the S&P U.S. Listed China 50 index, which is designed to track the performance of the 50 largest Chinese companies listed on U.S. exchanges by total market cap, stood at 3,696.92, marking a 7.3-percent gain for the month-to-date returns and a 29.24-percent slide for the year-to-date returns. Enditem